// ob doc
// 970114, Antcrusher

This documentation concerns the generic base inheritable ob.c.  Every other
"object" file inherits it in some fashion.  It sets up the basic functions
that are common to all of them.  Generally you should not inherit this
yourself, but inherit the object that is more specific to your application,
such as treasure, weapon, etc.

void set_id(string sArg);
void set_name(string sArg);

Both set IDs of the object to sArg, and the cap name to the cap of str.

void set_alias(string sArg);
void set_alt_name(string sArg);

Both of these also set IDs of the object.  If you want more than three valid
IDs for an object, you will need to write your own id() function, defined
below.

string query_name();

This returns the string set by set_name and set_id.  It is the "primary"
name of the object.

int id(string sArg);

This returns 0 if sArg does not match one of the valid IDs of the object.

void set_short(string sArg);

Sets the short description to sArg.

string short();
string query_short();

Both return the short_desc string.

void set_long(string sArg);

Sets the long description to sArg.  Include your own newline character.

string long();
string query_long();

Both return the long description if it was set, else "You see nothing special."

varargs void set_value(int iV);

Sets the value to iV.  Some other inheritables, such as treasure, redefine
this with more than one argument, hence varargs.

int query_value();

Returns the base value of the object.  Buying and selling prices
are modified by the shop based on various factors.

void set_weight(int iW);

Sets the weight of the object to iW.

int query_weight();

Returns the weight of the object.

void set_info(string iI);

Sets an informational string.

string query_info();

Returns the information string.

void set_read(string sArg);

Sets a readable string on the object.  The description should make a note
that something can be read.

int read(string sArg);

If sArg corresponds to the item, this writes the string and returns 1.
Else it returns 0.

void set_new_type(int iT);

To set the object as an object type defined in types.h.  This is a
bitfield.  Multiple types can be bitwise-or'd together in the set.

int query_new_type();

Returns the number set above.  Used as a bitfield.

string *query_type_strings(int iNew_type);

Returns an array of strings corresponding to which bits are supplied by
the argument iNew_type.

void set_material(int iM);

To set the object as being of a material defined in material.h.  This
is a bitfield.  Multiple materials can be bitwise-or'd together in
the set.
Ex.  set_material(MAT_WOOD|MAT_GOLD);

int query_material();

Returns the number set above.  Used as a bitfield.

string *query_material_strings(int iMaterial_type);

Returns an array of strings corresponding to which bits are supplied by
the argument material_type.

string *query_treasure_strings(int iTreasure_type);

Returns an array of strings corresponding to which bits are supplied by
the argument iTreasure_type.

void set_no_buy(int iI);

Set to 1 if it's not buyable.

int query_no_buy();

Returns buyable status.

void set_no_sell(int iI);

Pass a 1 as the parameter to have it be refused in stores. Note that this
works a bit differently from no_buy, in that the more times you call
set_no_sell(1), the more times you then have to call set_no_sell(0) to
get it to a sellable state again. This is done so that the creator can
set it no_sell, and if a guild uses no_sell to prohibit players from selling
checked-out/borrowed items, when the guild calls set_no_sell(0) when the
object is done being borrowed, the item will still not be sellable.

int query_no_sell(); 

Returns sellable status.

void set_no_clean_up(int iI);

Set this to avoid having this object, or any rooms/containers
containing this object, cleaned up.

int query_no_clean_up();

Returns the clean up setting.

void set_steal(int iI);

Set to 1 if it's not stealable.

int query_steal();

Returns nonstealability status.  (Yes, these should have been called
no_steal, but they weren't.)

void set_cursed(int iI);

Set i from 0-100 as the percent chance the item will be cursed, and
be stuck with the player.

status query_cursed();

Returns 1 if the item is cursed, else 0.

void set_unique();

Marks an item as unique.

int query_unique();

Returns 1 if the item is unique, else 0.

void set_keep(int iArg);

int query_keep();

Returns the value set by the above.

|GKBvarargs void set_object_destruct_timer(int iTime, mixed xFunc);|WK0

  |WKOThis function will destruct the object in iTime seconds. If
  xFunc is defined and is a closure, it will apply the function
  before destructing it. If it's a string, it will tell_room
  or tell_object of the environment of the object before destructing 
  it.
